          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>We start by the most pedestrian of approaches: quivers as directed graphs.</fr:p>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>245</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">quivers-0004</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>quivers-0004.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Quivers I">Quivers I</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>6</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>19</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link type="local" href="rui.xml" addr="rui" title="Rui Peixoto">Rui Peixoto</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>A quiver consists of:</fr:p>
                <fr:ul><fr:li>a set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> of <fr:em>vertices</fr:em>;</fr:li>
	<fr:li>a set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex> of <fr:em>edges</fr:em>;</fr:li>
	<fr:li>a pair of functions <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s, t \colon  E \rightarrow  V]]></fr:tex> named <fr:em>source</fr:em> and <fr:em>target</fr:em> maps.</fr:li></fr:ul>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>Two sets, and two functions, that's it! Moreover, these carry very intuitive meanings. Consider the following example of a quiver.</fr:p>
            <fr:figure>
              <fr:resource hash="2e8d29a861d18feb7f21b0c9c0c0b65e">
                <fr:resource-content>
                  <fr:img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," />
                </fr:resource-content>
                <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[
		\usepackage {tikz}
		\usepackage {tikz-cd}
	]]></fr:resource-source>
                <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
		\begin {tikzcd}
		a \arrow [r, "v"] & b
		\end {tikzcd}
	]]></fr:resource-source>
              </fr:resource>
            </fr:figure>
            <fr:p>This consists of vertices <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V = \{a, b\}]]></fr:tex> and a single edge <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E = \{v\}]]></fr:tex>.
The source and target maps encode the information that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> has a source <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s(v) = a]]></fr:tex> and target <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[t(v) = b]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Equivalently, we could define edges <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v \in  E]]></fr:tex> as ordered pairs <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(a, b) \in  V \times  V]]></fr:tex>, with entries the source and target vertices, respectively.</fr:p>
